    },
    {
      "id": "tT7s-0VqOrlVs5veWo_Pt",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1471.362373921342,
      "y": 75041.62599580291,
      "width": 341,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bko",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2096550741,
      "version": 40,
      "versionNonce": 1968101973,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773925898714,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How it will reach to container?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How it will reach to container?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "IddOb6yfEvV2di29YbAqX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1514.741280171342,
      "y": 75079.65333955291,
      "width": 880,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bkp",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 446826773,
      "version": 576,
      "versionNonce": 806378299,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773926141668,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "To make it reach to container, what we do is internally whatever request\nis coming to different port number like 8080, when I will get request from\n8080 we will redirect it to container's port number 80. and container's port\n80 has a web server already running or VM ka port 80. this can be done\nVM to VM, base to base, base to VM it can work any ways. When we get request on \n1 port number, we forward it to another that is called patting",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "To make it reach to container, what we do is internally whatever request\nis coming to different port number like 8080, when I will get request from\n8080 we will redirect it to container's port number 80. and container's port\n80 has a web server already running or VM ka port 80. this can be done\nVM to VM, base to base, base to VM it can work any ways. When we get request on \n1 port number, we forward it to another that is called patting",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ls1sAWJ0IyR0yYLKsRxQE",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1074.897530171342,
      "y": 75357.50880830291,
      "width": 462,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bkr",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1484327035,
      "version": 51,
      "versionNonce": 213660763,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773926180929,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How we will do it in Docker Container? -> ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How we will do it in Docker Container? -> ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Me-rQTHsD0y7uPlFUg39S",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1143.518623921342,
      "y": 75398.09474580291,
      "width": 1166,
      "height": 500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bks",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1515397525,
      "version": 777,
      "versionNonce": 1799525909,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773926799583,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Launch a Nginx container, that can be used as web server not a good aproach but can be used as\na web server.\n\ndocker run -d nginx -> nginx container is running in background\n\nNow we will install a networking software(net-tools) on our base system\napt-get install net-tools\n\nnet-tools is a pack of multiple softwares, there is one software that we use here is netstat, netstat show\nus all the thing that are going on for tcp and udp port.\n\nsudo netstat -tnlp -> it will show us tcp services running\nsudo netstat -unlp -> it will show us udp services runing\nsudo netstat -tunlp -> it will show all tcp and udp services running\n\nRight now we are concerned with tcp service\n\nrun\nsudo netstat -tnlp\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Launch a Nginx container, that can be used as web server not a good aproach but can be used as\na web server.\n\ndocker run -d nginx -> nginx container is running in background\n\nNow we will install a networking software(net-tools) on our base system\napt-get install net-tools\n\nnet-tools is a pack of multiple softwares, there is one software that we use here is netstat, netstat show\nus all the thing that are going on for tcp and udp port.\n\nsudo netstat -tnlp -> it will show us tcp services running\nsudo netstat -unlp -> it will show us udp services runing\nsudo netstat -tunlp -> it will show all tcp and udp services running\n\nRight now we are concerned with tcp service\n\nrun\nsudo netstat -tnlp\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "PBufqoLyQHjEeidOwfGYR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1145.420967671342,
      "y": 75924.57912080291,
      "width": 814,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bku",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1613354197,
      "version": 93,
      "versionNonce": 1165807477,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773926866857,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now we have anyway to reach till port 80? Can we reach our here by someway",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now we have anyway to reach till port 80? Can we reach our here by someway",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "KoPYpMWMaPyMeipJ5vbw3",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1200.448311421342,
      "y": 75965.43068330291,
      "width": 1078,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bkv",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 807226107,
      "version": 670,
      "versionNonce": 1376133653,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773927366839,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "No\nSo what we will do , we will start one more nginx container and in this we will create a bridge\nto reach till port 80. and to create the bridge command is\n\ndocker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx -> if anything come to 8080 it will redirect to container port 80, \n                                -p is for patting.\n\nNow we need to enable port 8080 in security groups in our EC2 instance\n\nGo to security Group\nAdd a custom TCP rule on port 8080 and allow it from anywhere in the world\nthen hit http://publicipofEC2:8080 in the browser\n\nNow deploying a webserver is hardly a 1 sec thing",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "No\nSo what we will do , we will start one more nginx container and in this we will create a bridge\nto reach till port 80. and to create the bridge command is\n\ndocker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx -> if anything come to 8080 it will redirect to container port 80, \n                                -p is for patting.\n\nNow we need to enable port 8080 in security groups in our EC2 instance\n\nGo to security Group\nAdd a custom TCP rule on port 8080 and allow it from anywhere in the world\nthen hit http://publicipofEC2:8080 in the browser\n\nNow deploying a webserver is hardly a 1 sec thing",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
