      "updated": 1774017546350,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now question is why not script why dockerfile?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now question is why not script why dockerfile?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "STsq465jbntKaUnvq2n9Z",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1301.0147176713417,
      "y": 81004.70802705291,
      "width": 1144,
      "height": 650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blb",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 539076813,
      "version": 2510,
      "versionNonce": 1648205229,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1774018752862,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "when infra development or deployment becomes easy becomes fast, people tend to deploy more\ninfra which means more kind of application or microservices , more versions of applications\neverything is more. When there are multiple kind of application or microservice each one of\nthem lets say its own container or their own image. Each application will have atleast their\nown image, When we have application 1 image, if we will launch a container, my version 1 is out\nor deployed, Version 2 same way we have a image, we will run a container and deploy simple as \nthat, Now the problem is whatever changes we are doint with all these commands who is keeping\na track of what changes are done in which container, there is no track of it Or what changes are\ndone in which image, Each image is modified from its base image, like we pickup a base ubuntu,\nwe modify and modify we make up a new container image. Or we pick up a modified image and we \nmodify it more and pack it as a new image. this always happens but whatever base we are taking\nand whatever modifications we are doing, who is keeping a track of it Noone, \nWe have noticed we have write two ways of making a container or dealing with a image, One thing\nwas when we pack a image to a tar file, Another way was when there was a running container, we \nmake a tar file out of it. From this tar now we will make a image. Both of these will have diff \nof metadata first with metadata another without metadata. Like second way the issue is here we\nhave noone who is keeping track of this. What is happening behind this.\n\nWhen we write a dockerfile and we execute it like a docker command, docker has a way of modifying\nimage in such a way that each change is kept track of. Each change is labeled and keep track of.\nThis is why we use dockerfile.\n\nNow if we have to move from application version 1 to version 2, we can just create dockerfile version1\nand version2, and this version 2 with slightly more changes, and it willl help us to deploy dockerfile\nversion 2. So that part is also very simple. Everything becomes simple here, complete deployment becomes\nsimple here, container management, image management everything becomes free",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "when infra development or deployment becomes easy becomes fast, people tend to deploy more\ninfra which means more kind of application or microservices , more versions of applications\neverything is more. When there are multiple kind of application or microservice each one of\nthem lets say its own container or their own image. Each application will have atleast their\nown image, When we have application 1 image, if we will launch a container, my version 1 is out\nor deployed, Version 2 same way we have a image, we will run a container and deploy simple as \nthat, Now the problem is whatever changes we are doint with all these commands who is keeping\na track of what changes are done in which container, there is no track of it Or what changes are\ndone in which image, Each image is modified from its base image, like we pickup a base ubuntu,\nwe modify and modify we make up a new container image. Or we pick up a modified image and we \nmodify it more and pack it as a new image. this always happens but whatever base we are taking\nand whatever modifications we are doing, who is keeping a track of it Noone, \nWe have noticed we have write two ways of making a container or dealing with a image, One thing\nwas when we pack a image to a tar file, Another way was when there was a running container, we \nmake a tar file out of it. From this tar now we will make a image. Both of these will have diff \nof metadata first with metadata another without metadata. Like second way the issue is here we\nhave noone who is keeping track of this. What is happening behind this.\n\nWhen we write a dockerfile and we execute it like a docker command, docker has a way of modifying\nimage in such a way that each change is kept track of. Each change is labeled and keep track of.\nThis is why we use dockerfile.\n\nNow if we have to move from application version 1 to version 2, we can just create dockerfile version1\nand version2, and this version 2 with slightly more changes, and it willl help us to deploy dockerfile\nversion 2. So that part is also very simple. Everything becomes simple here, complete deployment becomes\nsimple here, container management, image management everything becomes free",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
