      "updated": 1775658943307,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Why do we need Docker?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Why do we need Docker?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "6YWmCi2xairVzhCTqtons",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1524.944405171342,
      "y": 85543.02833955291,
      "width": 1232,
      "height": 800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bmE",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1270050897,
      "version": 2888,
      "versionNonce": 595379103,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775660369258,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Because VMs are heavy, Due to VM contains all these heavy things like Utility S/W, Applicatoin S/W,\nKernel individually, \nif these are already in base then why not to share, in Docker these things are shared.\n\nEarlier VMs were designed with the perspective that it can launch on windows system or any system, because\nit is having separate kernel of  linux.\n\nBut with Docker what was happen is, why to have this separate kernel, assuming that most of the corporate \nlevel deployments or even when we are making datacenters and all what's happening is on the base when they \nare making data centers also they are having kernel of linux only or the OS of linux only. SO kernel is\nof linux, Binaries is of Linux, Utility and application softwares they are of linux and then on top of it\nwhat if I just put a hypervisor that allows me to share these things, rather than me having separately\ninstalled, How about something that can allow us to share these things from base so for that purpose we \nstarted with Docker.\n\nBecause we are sharing, what now we need is a separate and a very minimal set of binaries, these minimal set\nof binaries are so small.\nLets say on base we are having RetHat linux(RHEL), in RHEL we use package manager us Yum like apt in ubuntu,\nanother one which is there which is RPM(RedHat Package Manager) these are the two that we mostly use in RHEL\nbased system or CentOS based system or Fedora Systems. But lets say we need a Ubuntu like environment, so with\nthese hypervisor we are getting isolated environment in this isolated environment which is behaving like a\nnew system, lets say I want package manager as dpkg or apt over here, so these are minimal binaries that we need\nSo why we need othere software, whenever we need that we can install, so we just need binaries to give new look\nand feel of new OS. and we have a share linux kernel which can give us linux runtime environment on top of it\nwe can install any application that we need for example a webserver or a database server or a backer server \nanything , we can install it over here that is how we get a complete OS like thing. whihc is very light.\n\nIN terms of VM, they are pretty heavy, they take 20 GB HDD very common for a VM, take 4-8 GB of RAM, can easily\ntake 5-20 minute for VM.\n\nwith docker we launch container and this container can be launch roughly in 2 sec this much fast.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Because VMs are heavy, Due to VM contains all these heavy things like Utility S/W, Applicatoin S/W,\nKernel individually, \nif these are already in base then why not to share, in Docker these things are shared.\n\nEarlier VMs were designed with the perspective that it can launch on windows system or any system, because\nit is having separate kernel of  linux.\n\nBut with Docker what was happen is, why to have this separate kernel, assuming that most of the corporate \nlevel deployments or even when we are making datacenters and all what's happening is on the base when they \nare making data centers also they are having kernel of linux only or the OS of linux only. SO kernel is\nof linux, Binaries is of Linux, Utility and application softwares they are of linux and then on top of it\nwhat if I just put a hypervisor that allows me to share these things, rather than me having separately\ninstalled, How about something that can allow us to share these things from base so for that purpose we \nstarted with Docker.\n\nBecause we are sharing, what now we need is a separate and a very minimal set of binaries, these minimal set\nof binaries are so small.\nLets say on base we are having RetHat linux(RHEL), in RHEL we use package manager us Yum like apt in ubuntu,\nanother one which is there which is RPM(RedHat Package Manager) these are the two that we mostly use in RHEL\nbased system or CentOS based system or Fedora Systems. But lets say we need a Ubuntu like environment, so with\nthese hypervisor we are getting isolated environment in this isolated environment which is behaving like a\nnew system, lets say I want package manager as dpkg or apt over here, so these are minimal binaries that we need\nSo why we need othere software, whenever we need that we can install, so we just need binaries to give new look\nand feel of new OS. and we have a share linux kernel which can give us linux runtime environment on top of it\nwe can install any application that we need for example a webserver or a database server or a backer server \nanything , we can install it over here that is how we get a complete OS like thing. whihc is very light.\n\nIN terms of VM, they are pretty heavy, they take 20 GB HDD very common for a VM, take 4-8 GB of RAM, can easily\ntake 5-20 minute for VM.\n\nwith docker we launch container and this container can be launch roughly in 2 sec this much fast.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
